## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to reason about secret management granularity, cache invalidation, and zero-downtime refresh.

## Key Concepts

- Secrets mounted as files via projected volumes
- In-app credential caching and refresh patterns
- Signals and inotify/fsnotify for reload
- Rolling updates vs hot reload

## Code Example

```javascript
// Node.js snippet: watch credential file and reload
const fs=require('fs');
let creds;
function load(){
  creds = fs.readFileSync('/var/secrets/db-creds','utf8');
}
load();
fs.watch('/var/secrets/db-creds',(ev, f)=>{ if(ev==='change'){ load(); /* refresh DB pool here */ }});
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you implement a Kubernetes-native approach to trigger a reload when secret rotates without application changes?
- What are trade-offs between in-pod reload vs restart and how to monitor?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical Kubernetes design for async processing, backpressure, idempotency, and delivery guarantees in production-like scenarios.

## Key Concepts
- Durable queues (Kafka/Redis Streams)
- Backpressure and rate limiting
- Idempotent workers and at-least-once delivery
- Backoff strategies and DLQ
- Data-store consistency with upserts

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-code: worker handling with idempotency checks
function handle(msg) {
  if (db.hasProcessed(msg.id)) return;
  const res = process(msg);
  db.upsert({ id: msg.id, result: res });
  ack(msg);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test exactly-once vs at-least-once guarantees?
- How would you observe and alert on backpressure and DLQ growth?

